{"author":{"id":"f270607f232f5ea3e06daa2368d41de7674a6d0d64158946f2581dde2c4881fc"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1773094150,"nonce":"ljtM81AOjjy1xPDODnG/FRrXSiY=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s7wCpQy","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/7770#issuecomment-4027225138"},"message":"This tool uses Galaxy's detected column types for tabular data and there can ever be only a single type per column. Because the first row has a float in column 4, subsequent column 4 values are expected to also be floats. The tool will also always try to convert all values on a row to their expected types, whether they are part of operations or not (this is because the tool has no insight into which columns compute expressions will operate on).\nSo your error has nothing to do with your expression or any ambiguity, it's just that not all values in column 4 are of the same type as the first one.\n\nFor cases like this one, you can use the *\"Autodetect column types\"* option from the *\"Error handling\"* section, then rewrite your expression as `float(c2)*float(c3)` (see the option help and the tool help).","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1773094397,"nonce":"EeknwKgHcVu5MMq9FiC+jAe6+x8=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s7wCuaI","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/7770#issuecomment-4027246216"},"message":"\u003e (this is because the tool has no insight into which columns compute expressions will operate on)\n\nand to explain this a bit: the tool leaves compute expression parsing to Python by turning the expression into a lambda function, which it then evaluates. It makes no attempt at all to parse out referenced columns itself and that's why it needs to convert all values of any row.","files":null}]}